igration history to show that even though migration issues were often considered "low stakes" or "low risk" by foreign policy professionals concerned with Cold War politics and the nuclear age, they were neither "no risk" nor unimportant to larger goals. Instead, migration diplomacy became a means of facilitating other foreign policy priorities, even when doing so came at great cost for migrants themselves.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 26. Mrz 2024) 0aChinesezUnited States. 0aCold War. 4aAsian American Studies. 4aAsian Studies. 4aU.S. History.  aChina, United States, Taiwan, U.S.-Chinese Relations, Cold War, Cold War politics, transnational migration, migration policies, migration diplomacy, migration legislation, migration controls, immigration, refugee, international student, deportation, Chinese-American, diplomatic history, foreign policy, foreign relations.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertCornell University Press Complete eBook-Package 2016z978311066749340uhttps://doi.org/10.7591/978150170147440uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781501701474423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781501701474/original  a978-3-11-066749-3  Cornell University Press Complete eBook-Package 2016b2016  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_PPALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles